qas.question: In languages like Thai and Icelandic, tenuis and aspirated consonants are what?
[p˭ s˭] and [pʰ ʰp sʰ] are separate what?
In the Armenian language, tenuis and unaspirated stops are what?

plausible_answers.text: Unaspirated consonants like [p˭ s˭] and aspirated consonants like [pʰ ʰp sʰ]
whether they have one or the other

context: In many languages, such as Armenian, Korean, Thai, Indo-Aryan languages, Dravidian languages, Icelandic, Ancient Greek, and the varieties of Chinese, tenuis and aspirated consonants are <a0_0><b2_0><b5_0>phonemic<b5_0/><b2_0/><a0_0/>. <b3_0>Unaspirated consonants like <b6_0>[p˭ s˭]<b6_0/> and aspirated consonants like [pʰ ʰp sʰ]<b3_0/> are separate <a1_0>phonemes<a1_0/>, and words are distinguished by <b4_0>whether they have one or the other<b4_0/>.
